## <span style="color: #4B0082;">Final Project: Urban Transportation Optimization with Graphs and Networks</span>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(to right, #4B0082, #6B238E); padding: 2px; margin: 20px 0;">
<div style="background-color: white; padding: 25px;">

### <span style="color: #DAA520;">Purpose</span>

Practical implementation in code, developing an urban network model that allows analyzing routes, flows, coloring, and structural properties of the system.

### <span style="color: #DAA520;">Objective</span>

Model and analyze an urban transportation network (bus routes, metro, or bicycle) using graph theory. Students must construct the graph, represent its properties mathematically, program search and traversal algorithms, apply the maximum flow–minimum cut theorem, and explore additional applications such as coloring and planarity.

</div>
</div>

---

### <span style="color: #4B0082;">Practical Case: Urban Transportation Network</span>

Modern cities face the challenge of optimizing their urban transportation. Buses and routes must be planned efficiently to minimize travel times, avoid congestion, and ensure connectivity between zones.

In this project, you will work with a simplified urban transportation network, where each node represents a stop and each edge represents a direct connection between stops (weighted by time or distance).

---

## <span style="color: #4B0082;">Instructions</span>

<div style="background-color: #4B0082; color: white; padding: 3px 20px; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;">

The project is divided into four phases corresponding to the course topics.

</div>

---

### <span style="color: #DAA520;">PHASE 1: Basic Concepts</span>

<div style="border: 2px solid #4B0082; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">

**Model the urban system:** Define what each vertex and each edge represents.

**Determine the graph characteristics:**

- Is it directed or undirected?
- Is it weighted (time or distance)?
- Is it connected?

**Calculate and analyze metrics:**

- Average degree, density, diameter
- Identify its type (simple graph, multigraph, tree, bipartite, etc.)

</div>

---

### <span style="color: #DAA520;">PHASE 2: Graph Representation</span>

<div style="border: 2px solid #4B0082; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">

**Mathematical representation:**

- Express your network as G = (V, E)
- Construct its adjacency matrix or adjacency list

**Computational representation:**

- Use Python (networkx) to build the graph from data
- Visualize it (using matplotlib or nx.draw)
- Show the data structure used and justify your choice

</div>

---

### <span style="color: #DAA520;">PHASE 3: Traversal and Search Algorithms</span>

<div style="border: 2px solid #4B0082; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">

**Shortest path:**

- Implement Dijkstra between two important stops
- Compare the optimal route with an alternative route

</div>

---

### <span style="color: #DAA520;">PHASE 4: Applications and Advanced Analysis</span>

<div style="border: 2px solid #4B0082; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; margin: 15px 0;">

**Planar graphs and surfaces:**

- Evaluate if the main subgraph can be represented without crossings (planarity), using Euler's formula
- Draw the planar graph if possible

**Graph coloring:**

- Apply a heuristic (Greedy, Welsh–Powell)
- Interpret colors as bus shifts or service zones

**Network flow:**

- Model passenger flow (or units) between two stations: source (terminal) and sink (destination zone)
- Assign capacities to edges (maximum number of passengers or units)
- Calculate maximum flow and verify the Maximum Flow–Minimum Cut theorem

**Graph mapping:**

- Group zones (supernodes) and analyze how connectivity changes

</div>

---

